const proposalMarkdown = `# AI Learning & Knowledge Infrastructure
### A Proposal to the AI Alliance

---

We're proposing a learning and knowledge-mapping program to help Canadian social impact organizations build genuine fluency in community-owned AI tools — and connect with the broader ecosystem of organizations already using them.

---

## The Program

**Learning Events**

A structured series of peer-driven sessions at three levels, delivered on open video platforms with recordings shared in a commons. Weekly drop-in coworking and one-on-one calls provide ongoing support between sessions.

- **Introductory** — Shared context-setting; surfacing what members already know and do
- **Skills** — Practical, jargon-free sessions on digital knowledge portability, basic tooling (command line, code editors, AI assistants), and evaluating any tech stack for real ownership and control
- **Technical deep-dives** — Co-designed with members; practitioner workshops on local model deployment, federated data, and open-source agent frameworks; knowledge mobilization labs for moving community knowledge into interoperable formats

**Peer Support & Knowledge Mapping**

- Weekly drop-in office hours and coworking sessions, hosted by public goods and AI Alliance member communities
- Scheduled one-on-one calls for focused problem-solving
- Direct access to contributor networks for deploying knowledge resources and open-source, privacy-preserving AI tooling
- Technical sensemaking for founders and leads: translating non-technically-stated operational challenges into specific, searchable language — and surfacing dissonance between stated business needs and worker experience before it derails a project
- Mapping existing social tech projects across Canada's bioregions; asset mapping and knowledge graphing of the AI Alliance ecosystem on Geo Protocol; connecting members to bioregional and domain-specific knowledge commons

---

## Budget & Resourcing

Target: **CAD $55,000–$115,000**, shared across two funding streams.

| Stream | Target |
|---|---|
| Participant co-funding | CAD $30,000–$50,000 |
| Web3 sponsorship | USD $25,000–$50,000 |

**Co-funders** contribute on a pay-what-you-can basis (target: 3–5 organizations at CAD $10,000 each) and receive curriculum input, a dedicated privacy-preserving AI assistant for their own knowledge management, and additional one-on-one and group support.

**Web3 sponsors** (Near Protocol, Anoma, Celo, and comparable networks) receive content input, live access to Alliance members, brand placement in relevant sessions, and free Bioregional Builder slots for Canada-based AI infrastructure projects.

Program resources are governed through a purpose-built, time-limited DAO, dissolved at project close. All financial flows are on public distributed ledgers.

**Labor** is contributed by a distributed network drawing from AI Alliance member organizations and aligned networks: Green Pill Network, Bread Cooperative, OpenCivics Labs, and Gaia AI.

---

## What We're Asking For

1. **Co-funding commitments** — Even soft or conditional commitments give us a credible signal of demand when approaching web3 sponsors.
2. **Permission to name the Alliance in sponsor outreach** — Any formal partnership agreements will come back to you for review before signing.
3. **Feedback and topic requests** — What questions are most pressing for your members? What domains are most represented in your network? Early input shapes the curriculum most.`;
---

